      Sports ownership
   =20
 =20

Professional sports is a glamourous business, and people are willing to pay=
 money to be associated with its glamour. Fans will pay money to go to game=
s, television networks will pay money to broadcast games, companies will pa=
y money to put their logos on uniforms, cities will pay money to build stad=
iums to attract teams, rich people will pay a premium to own teams, etc.; t=
here are all sorts of ways to exchange money for glamour.
Traditionally the=C2=A0players of the sport are the=C2=A0source=C2=A0of the=
 glamour, and therefore much of the money flows from fans/television/sponso=
rs to them. (Through the owners, who get a cut.) That=E2=80=99s why it=E2=
=80=99s =E2=80=9Cprofessional=E2=80=9D sports, because the players get paid=
. Athletes who can do amazing things generate glamour, which they sell to f=
ans.
But that doesn=E2=80=99t have to=C2=A0always=C2=A0be the case. You could ch=
arge the players? Like, a lot of people want to go watch the Yankees, but p=
robably a lot of people would also like to be able to say that they played=
=C2=A0for the Yankees. Maybe auction off a few roster spots? There is a bal=
ance to be struck here: I suspect you could find a few hedge fund managers =
who would pay a lot of money to be Lionel Messi=E2=80=99s teammate for a ga=
me, but if Inter Miami fielded a team made up of the 11 highest bidders the=
n most of the glamour would be lost. (I would still watch this?) Frankly if=
 there=C2=A0were, like,=C2=A0five=C2=A0roster spots in any professional spo=
rt reserved for the highest bidder, that would suck a lot of the glamour ou=
t of those spots. But one? Maybe that=E2=80=99s something?

Early this year, a struggling soccer team in Portugal=E2=80=99s second divi=
sion unveiled a new player to help in its battle against relegation. He did=
n=E2=80=99t look like anyone=E2=80=99s idea of a star signing.
Courtney Reum is a middle-aged American venture capitalist whose soccer car=
eer peaked a couple of decades earlier, when he played for Columbia in the =
Ivy League.=C2=A0
That didn=E2=80=99t prevent Reum from earning a contract with L=C3=A4nk FC =
Vilaverdense. On Jan. 31, the final day of European soccer=E2=80=99s midsea=
son transfer window, the club confirmed the former Goldman Sachs investment=
 banker as the newest member of its squad.
Vilaverdense took a chance on Reum=E2=80=94enticed by more than his sports =
skills. Reum=E2=80=99s deal with the team included a loan, described as in =
the six figures, to ease the club=E2=80=99s financial pressure, as well as =
potential future investment and access to Reum=E2=80=99s extensive business=
 and finance network. =E2=80=A6
In the waning minutes of Vilaverdense=E2=80=99s crucial game against Torree=
nse, Reum jogged onto the pitch for his pro debut.=C2=A0
=E2=80=9CIt hasn=E2=80=99t quite sunk in,=E2=80=9D Reum said afterward. =E2=
=80=9CI genuinely felt great out there. I felt like I could do something.=
=E2=80=9D

He did not, and they were relegated, but he had fun, and I suppose the mone=
y will help them in the third division.
