<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Professional sports is a glamourous business, =
and people are willing to pay money to be associated with its glamour. Fans=
 will pay money to go to games, television networks will pay money to broad=
cast games, companies will pay money to put their logos on uniforms, cities=
 will pay money to build stadiums to attract teams, rich people will pay a =
premium to own teams, etc.; there are all sorts of ways to exchange money f=
or glamour.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Traditionally the=C2=A0<em>players </em>of the=
 sport are the=C2=A0<em>source=C2=A0</em>of the glamour, and therefore much=
 of the money flows from fans/television/sponsors to them. (Through the own=
ers, who get a cut.) That=E2=80=99s why it=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Cprofessional=
=E2=80=9D sports, because the players get paid. Athletes who can do amazing=
 things generate glamour, which they sell to fans.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But that doesn=E2=80=99t have to=C2=A0<em>alwa=
ys=C2=A0</em>be the case. You could charge the players? Like, a lot of peop=
le want to go watch the Yankees, but probably a lot of people would also li=
ke to be able to say that they <em>played=C2=A0</em>for the Yankees. Maybe =
auction off a few roster spots? There is a balance to be struck here: I sus=
pect you could find a few hedge fund managers who would pay a lot of money =
to be Lionel Messi=E2=80=99s teammate for a game, but if Inter Miami fielde=
d a team made up of the 11 highest bidders then most of the glamour would b=
e lost. (I would still watch this?) Frankly if there=C2=A0were, like,=C2=A0=
<em>five=C2=A0</em>roster spots in any professional sport reserved for the =
highest bidder, that would suck a lot of the glamour out of those spots. Bu=
t one? <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35310612.25=
6343/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9saWZlc3R5bGUvcHJvLXNvY2Nlci1yb29raWUtY291cn=
